[With the beginning of winter, deer mice are likely to move into houses and outbuildings with the onset of cold weather. The precautions noted above are good ones to reduce the risk of exposure to Sin Nombre virus. Although infections are rare, including in New Mexico, HPS is a very serious disease and the case fatality rate is relatively high, especially if medical attention is sought late in the course of the infection.

As noted in the report above, the rodent host of Sin Nombre virus is the deer mouse, _Peromyscus maniculatus_; an image can be seen at http://www.nsf.gov/news/mmg/media/images/mouse_f.jpg.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of New Mexico in the southwestern USA can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3032107,233. - Mod.TY]
